Dimention reduction methods on number of accidents in OECD countries for years 2000-2018 (Part 2)

Maria Janiszewska


Introduction

This is a second part of the analysis of the number of accidents. In this paper I will present methods of dimensions reduction: multidimensional scaling (MDS) and Principal component analysis (PCA).

Dimensions reduction


MDS - multidimensional scaling

First method of dimensions reduction is MDS. The data set consist of the continuous variables, thus the MDS is metric. Below there is a plot of MDS for years (normalized data). We can see that data provides a quite smooth plot in the two dimensions and additionally years from 2014 to 2018 are quite similar. For now it’s hard to say if there is an outlier among them.

dist.data2<-dist(data2.normal) # distance between units
autoplot(cmdscale(dist.data2, eig = TRUE), label = TRUE, label.size = 3)

As is visible is the picture below 4 dimensions are enough to get a very high value of R squared.

r <- cmdscale(dist.data2, eig=TRUE)
plot(cumsum(r$eig) / sum(r$eig), 
       type="h", lwd=5, las=1, 
       xlab="Number of dimensions", 
       ylab=expression(R^2))


Goodnes of fit

As we can see on the plot below we can see the correlation between the data is high for most of the observations. Thus I tried function sim2diss() for Stress Majorization of a Complicated Function to transform the data and the which impact of observation for stress function.

sim<-cor(data2.normal)
corrplot(sim,tl.cex=0.01)

dis2<-sim2diss(sim, method=1, to.dist=TRUE)
fit.data<-mds(dis2, ndim=4,  type="ratio")
fit.data
## 
## Call:
## mds(delta = dis2, ndim = 4, type = "ratio")
## 
## Model: Symmetric SMACOF 
## Number of objects: 44 
## Stress-1 value: 0.106 
## Number of iterations: 36
# plot with impact of observation for stress function
plot(fit.data, pch=21, cex=as.numeric(fit.data$spp), bg="purple" )


Mantel test for similarity

Mantel test is a test for correlation between two matrices. It is used to check if transformed matrix did not lose the most important characteristics.

mantel.test(as.matrix(sim), as.matrix(dis2)) 
## $z.stat
## [1] -204.6826
## 
## $p
## [1] 0.001
## 
## $alternative
## [1] "two.sided"

P - value of Mantel test is equal to 0.001, based on which we reject the null hypothesis H0 about significant difference between the simple correlation matrix and the one with stress function. Thus the matrices are similar.


Goodnes of fit of MDS

The next step is to check Goodnes of fit of MDS. To do this I used Kruskal’s stress (that was calculated above) and random stress function.

# random stress function 
stressvec<-randomstress(n=19, ndim=4, nrep=1) 

(ratio <- fit.data$stress/ mean(stressvec))
## [1] 0.2858386

As we can see the value of ratio is close to 0.3. That is a quite poor result. Even adding more dimensions do not improve results. That gives an incentive to look for another method of which will give better explanation.


PCA

Simple PCA


PCA is another method of dimension reduction. To perform a PCA first trying should be data normalization. After this I checked the distribution of the data. After normalization distribution is much closed to normal however the middle section is too low as for the normal distribution.

When it comes to loadings (rotation) the values are also very small - only some of them are getting close to 0.3. These small values can be not good enough to analize the results. To enchance the values and at the same time maximize the variance shared among the factors I prepared Rotated PCA, which is presented in the next section.

Rotated PCA

One of the types of PCA is rotated PCA. Using a specific algorithms which are looking for the simplest possible structure - for example varimax - we get results that are easier to interpret. However after using this we lose part of variance explanation. I used principal() function to do so.
Table below presents loadings. We can see which countries have high value of loading in each column.

X.pca2<-principal(data2.normal, nfactors=4, rotate="varimax")
print(loadings(X.pca2), digits=3, cutoff=0.4, sort=TRUE)

Quality of rotated PCA


For rotated PCA there a few measures based on which we can characterize the quality.


Complexity

Complexity tells us level of how much factors are hard to interpretation. The lower value the batter. Here we can see that 25 factor (Latvia) is the most complex. However there are some countries that are only a little less complicated.

plot(X.pca2$complexity, pch = 16, xlim=c(-20, 110), main="Complexity of factors", xlab=" ", ylab="complexity", col = "purple", cex =0.5)
pointLabel(X.pca2$complexity, labels=names(X.pca2$complexity), cex=0.8)

Uniquenesses

Another measure of quality is Uniquenesses, which points out the part of variance that is unique for a factor (best scenario is assigned only to one). The best value are low and close to zero. On ple plot below there are a lot of factors that seems to be quite unique which is a good information. The higher value is for factor number 36 (Moldova) which is close to 0.5. Nevertheless it is still quite a low value.

plot(X.pca2$uniqueness, pch = 16, xlim=c(-20, 110), main="Uniqueness of factors", xlab=" ", ylab="complexity",col = "purple", cex =0.5)
pointLabel(X.pca2$uniqueness, labels=names(X.pca2$uniqueness), cex=0.8)

Conclusions

Analysis of the data set were a base of the analysis with MDS method and PCA. As it seemed the appropriate number of dimensions MDS was equal to 4. However as it turned out the goodness of fit was poor. This conclusion was made after Kruskal’s stress and random function where ration was too big. As for the PCA I used both simple and rotated versions of the model. One of the findings of comparing model without outlier to the rotated PCA with outlier was that the results are much better for the former. Moreover - results were promising - conclusion made based on Complexity and Uniqueness. For this kind of data the better option to use for the analysis is rotated PCA. However the data set was very small so there was no sense to conduct prediction. There is an incentive to broaden analysis and get more data that will be used in the next analysis.
